1'1-12. Divination hy sortes (cp. also r, 8, 33 2, 5, 13) was widespread in Italy and prevalent from the earliest times. Their use was general in the various temples (the most famous being the temple of Fortuna at Praeneste, cp. also the famous sortes Vergilianoe of a later date); but sortilegi also plied their trade in the Circus aud other crowded parts of the city (Hor. Sat. 1, 6, 114; 1, 9, 303 Cicero, Dio. 1, 1323 Juv. 6, 583, ete). The sortes were pieces of wood or other material inscribed with some conveniently indefinite state- ment. These were placed iu an uru (situla, Plautus, Casino, 359 fl, etc.) and shuffled. Tbeu one, or one at a time, was drawn out and its meaning inter- preted hythe sortilegus (cp. the amusing passage in Apuleius, Met. 9, 8). The two lines before us describe Delia’s method of consulting the sortes to find whether it will be saie for Tib. to go with Messalla.
